    	<li id="comment-4971" class="comment c14 c-y2010 c-m11 c-d08 c-h15 alt depth-1">
    		<div class="comment-author vcard"><img alt='' src='http://www.gravatar.com/avatar/585e400d21005625ded1e212386b159c?s=80&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.gravatar.com%2Favatar%2Fad516503a11cd5ca435acc9bb6523536%3Fs%3D80&amp;r=G' class='photo avatar avatar-80 photo' height='80' width='80' /> <span class="fn n"><a href='http://zft.us.edu.pl/kostur' rel='external nofollow' class='url url'>Marcin Kostur</a></span></div>
    		<div class="comment-meta">Posted November 8, 2010 at 15:36 <span class="meta-sep">|</span> <a href="#comment-4971" title="Permalink to this comment">Permalink</a></div>
                <div class="comment-content">
        		<p>Nice story, </p>
<p>The sailing against the wind is not an intuitive, mostly because there is no simple mathematical formula for the underlying physics. However one can do some convincing models.<br />
I have some matlab code which can, probably in the simplest way, demonstrate theoretically the principle. In short, if it is possible do sail down the wind faster the the wind than by having rotating sail (blades) DDWFTTW is possible.  See:  <a href="http://goo.gl/TtEfM" rel="nofollow">http://goo.gl/TtEfM</a></p>
<p>The best </p>
<p>Marcin</p>
    		</div>
